Kyle's Findings - Deep Learning Convolutional Neural Network Capstone:¶

  • Facial Emotion Detection using Supervised Learning Image Analysis Capstone Project

Executive Summary¶

Key Takeaways:

  • identify and focus on the big picture first and all of its components

    • This notebook explores multiple configurations of basic neural networks, transfer learning approaches, and deep complex neural networks are designed, trained, and tested.

    • These models are being trained and designed to recognize and correctly predict human emotional facial expressions as low-res grayscale images.

    • My approach to the model building was to decrease the filter count as the network deepened. My intuition was to start with many filters to catch as many potential features as possible early. As the model deepens the filter count reduces to provide more nuanced understanding of the data in the network.

    • Minimal MaxPooling utilization because data images are so small, reducing their feature complexity wouldn't be helpful.

    • Minimal Dropout utilization, overfitting is addressed through early stopping. The size of the datasets already makes training tricky. More photos needs to be in the training set, dropout in this instance is a reduction in data that is needed. Address overfitting another way.

  • summarize the most imporant findings and takeaways in the beginning

    • Overfit models occur often with neural networks, boundaries must be set up when training and running a model to prevent overfitting.

    • I A/B tested the grayscale vs RGB on the same model, only changed the color mode. The rgb color mode model scored nearly 4% lower than the grayscale model.

  • provide the final proposed model specifications

    • The final proposed model is the Fine-Tuned EfficientNet Model that was trained on the output of a 1st frozen EfficientNet Model.

    • The 1st model utilizes the EfficientNet training weights as they are and I add an ANN to this model to produce the facial expression class prediction.

    • This final model is the 1st model but the last 40 layers of the transferred network are unfrozen and allowed to train on the dataset in this project.

    • This transferred network was initially trained on a massive database of many different images beyond faces. By allowing a portion of the transferred layers to be trained on our data helps the model focus on the specific data patterns associated with faces.

Key Next Steps:

  • steps that can be taken to improve the solution

    • Best next step to improve any data driven solution is to review the data, it's labels, and add more photographic examples to train on.

    • Further exploration of model configurations, transfer model modifications, and application of data augmentation to help expand the dataset.

    • Explore ability to further divide the photographs into more categories. This would provide a method to help the model identify the subtle differences between facial expressions. Too few classes misses important nuances in the data and too easily miscategorizes.

  • how to make the best of the solution

    • To make the best of this solution, newly introduced datasets must be preprocessed in the same way as done for the initial training set.

    • Understand that the most commonly mis-identification are between 'happy' and 'neutral'. No immediate negative outcomes from this mix-up are apparent and to be avoided.

  • what are the steps to be followed by the stakeholders

    • The model performs well enough to deploy into the wild. The shortcommings of mixing up happy and neutral wont cause pain, loss, damage, or anything else that should be avoided.

    • As with most tools, this tool's shortcomings can be overcome by pairing this tool with other data to help fully contextualize the perceived facial expressions.

    • Use this tool as a launchpad to continue development and refinement of the model to continue to increase the effectiveness of the model over time.

Problem & Solution Summary:¶

what problem is being solved

  • The problem is determining if its possible to train a computer to accurately predict human emotions through facial expressions observed in low resolution grayscale images.

final proposed solution design

  • The final proposed solution's design is built on a series of EfficientNet Transfer Learning models:
  • The first model's transfered layers do not train while my additional layers will train on the transfered model's weights.
  • The second model utilizes the first model's output as input data. Define a function to unfreeze the last 40 layers of the model, allowing them to train further. The learning rate is reduced to facilitate the model's fine-tuning.

why is this a 'valid' solution that is likely to solve the problem

  • the reason for the proposed solution design

    • The proposed solution's accuracy of 75% & loss of 0.6131 are good performance numbers. This model is delployable & the miscategorizations are low. The pairing of 'happy' and 'neutral' performed worst, luckily these misclassifications are of little consequence.
    • Deployment allows utilization of the model's capabilities and advantages without big risks while solutions for the happy/neutral problem are engineered.

  • how does it affect the problem/business

    • The ability to recognize human emotions via facial expressions in low resolution grayscale imagery can be incredibly valuable information.
    • For example, retail businesses can utilize this model to non-verbally survey customer emotions as they enter, shop, and leave.

Recommendations for Implementation:¶

what are some key recommendations to implement the solution

  • This solution is just a tool. It is not a 1-size-fits-all solution machine, and no single tool can do an entire job on its own.
  • Additional training runs will improve the model's performance.
  • This model is designed to observe single images of a particular aspect ratio. Any problems with data outside these parameters need to be altered or a new model must be instantiated.

what are the key actionables for stakeholders

  • Continue to collect new data to use while maintaining a routine training schedule to steadily improve the model's performance.
  • Readings of 'happy' or 'neutral' emotions need extra scrutiny since they were the most difficult for the model to predict correctly.
  • Model is deployable, ready for new images to be input for predictions.

what is the expected benefit and/or costs

  • list the benefits of the solution

    • Humans communicate a lot through their faces and a computer that is able to accurately detect a human's emotion could react to the humans reaction during an interaction.

    • Unbiased customer survey of each moment they are in the store, facial expression emotion detection is good for this.

    • Unbiased employee emotion detection could help identify potential trouble, under/over worked, and many other things

    • A big cost to many is privacy. Constant filming of faces, data collected for training runs, the monitoring of actions for interpretation.

  • take some rational assumptions to put forward some numbers on costs/benefits for stakeholders

    • Short Term costs to integrate the new tool into current infrastructure and workflow.

    • Additional job position that needs employee to collect and maintain integrity of the production model.

what are the key risks and challenges

  • what are the potential risks or challenges of the proposed solution design

    • Biggest risk of any prediction model is poor predictions producing bad outcomes. Steady upkeep and additional data for the model will help avoid these errors.

    • Having the input data required to be a certain size requires time-consuming data preprocessing before the model sees it.

what further analysis needs to be done or what other associated problems need to be solved

  • More analysis of the network architecture configurations would help discover more effective model designs.

  • More photographs of faces, properly labeled, to train the model even more.

  • Divide up vauge emotions like 'neutral' into seperate groups of more subtle and direct emotions, i.e. fear, disgust, bored, intese, etc...

  • Taking the analysis of still images to interpret human emotions is a limited tool, iterating this tool for use in video and eventually into live-feed camera footage.

  • The model's restrict requirement of a certain aspect ratio is another limitation. Developing this tool and technique into a model that accepts any aspect ratio would be a powerful next step.

Facial Emotion Detection Full Analysis¶

Problem Definition¶

The context: Why is this problem important to solve?

  • The problem of identifying human facial emotions is an extremely important foundational function for any face tracking technologies. If only 1 emotion is considered a face then when a new emotional expression is observed by the computer it will not be registered as a face.

The objectives: What is the intended goal?

  • Additional and more nuanced reasons for being able to determine facial expressions can be incorporated into technologies that register unspoken communications, like a system that can track faces and emotions for customers as they enter the store, browse, and ultimately leave. Could be interesting data that could go undetected in a proper survey.

The key questions: What are the key questions that need to be answered?

  • Can a neural network structure really be able to see and interpret facial expression at all?
  • How many images and classified emotions are needed to make a robust and broad performing model?
  • What is the best approach to getting high performance results, build model's from scratch or utilize transfer learning to build on the work of past model training.

The problem formulation: What are we trying to solve using data science?

  • Through data science we are trying to interpret the patterns of pixel shades of many different images to be able to accurately recognize when an image is of a face with a certain expression.

About the dataset¶

The data set consists of 3 folders, i.e., 'test', 'train', and 'validation'. Each of these folders has four subfolders:

‘happy’: Images of people who have happy facial expressions.
‘sad’: Images of people with sad or upset facial expressions.
‘surprise’: Images of people who have shocked or surprised facial expressions.
‘neutral’: Images of people showing no prominent emotion in their facial expression at all.

DATADIR = '/content/Facial_emotion_images/train'
DATADIR_test = '/content/Facial_emotion_images/test'
DATADIR_validation = '/content/Facial_emotion_images/validation'
CATEGORIES = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise']
IMG_SIZE = 48

folder_path = 'Facial_emotion_images/'

Prep the Data¶

Since the dataset has multiple subfolders I want to set up a few variables and feature names before beginning.

In [6]:
# Here I am going to define a function to extract the images from the dataset
training_data = []

def make_training_data():
  for category in CATEGORIES:
    path = os.path.join(DATADIR, category)
    classifier_number = category

    for img in os.listdir(path):
      array01 = cv2.imread(os.path.join(path, img))
      array02 = cv2.resize(array01, (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE))
      training_data.append([array02, classifier_number])

make_training_data()

# make test data

test_data = []

def make_test_data():
  for category in CATEGORIES:
    path = os.path.join(DATADIR_test, category)
    classifier_number = category

    for img in os.listdir(path):
      array01_test = cv2.imread(os.path.join(path, img))
      array02_test = cv2.resize(array01_test, (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE))
      test_data.append([array02_test, classifier_number])

make_test_data()

# make validation data

validation_data = []

def make_validation_data():
  for category in CATEGORIES:
    path = os.path.join(DATADIR_validation, category)
    classifier_number = category

    for img in os.listdir(path):
      array01_validation = cv2.imread(os.path.join(path, img))
      array02_validation = cv2.resize(array01_validation, (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE))
      validation_data.append([array02_validation, classifier_number])

make_validation_data()

# encoding target variable

y_train_encoded = []

for label_name in y_train['Label']:
    if(label_name == 'sad'):
      y_train_encoded.append(0)

    if(label_name == 'neutral'):
      y_train_encoded.append(1)

    if(label_name == 'happy'):
      y_train_encoded.append(2)

    if(label_name == 'surprise'):
      y_train_encoded.append(3)

y_train_encoded = to_categorical(y_train_encoded, 4)
print(y_train_encoded)

Visualizing our Classes¶

Let's look at our classes.

Write down your observation for each class. What do you think can be a unique feature of each emotion, that separates it from the remaining classes?

Happy¶

In [ ]:
# create a for loop to draw random samples from the dataset to visualize
happy_faces = [fn for fn in os.listdir(f'{DATADIR}/{CATEGORIES[0]}')]
select_happy = np.random.choice(happy_faces, 12, replace = False)

fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12, 12))

for i in range(12):
  ax = fig.add_subplot(4, 3, i + 1)
  fp = f'{DATADIR}/{CATEGORIES[0]}/{select_happy[i]}'
  fn = load_img(fp, target_size = (100, 100))
  plt.imshow(fn)
  plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

Observations and Insights:__

  • A few characteristics that would make good identifying traits for the emotion displayed in these photos are:
    • Teeth showing, mouth open, eyebrows raised, eyes a bit squinted.
    • Head tilted backward, lines along mouth, nose, and chin.
    • rounded cheekbones from upper lip raising exposing teeth, 'crow's feet' lines on outer sides of the eyes

Sad¶

In [ ]:
# Duped the for loop that draws random samples from the dataset to visualize and adjusted to the correct data source
sad_faces = [fn for fn in os.listdir(f'{DATADIR}/{CATEGORIES[2]}')]
select_sad = np.random.choice(sad_faces, 12, replace = False)

fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12, 12))

for i in range(12):
  ax = fig.add_subplot(4, 3, i + 1)
  fp = f'{DATADIR}/{CATEGORIES[2]}/{select_sad[i]}'
  fn = load_img(fp, target_size = (150, 150))
  plt.imshow(fn)
  plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

Observations and Insights:__

  • A few characteristics that would make good identifying traits for the emotion displayed in these photos are:
    • a furrowed brow causing lines and creases at the top of the nose between eyebrows and low on the forehead.
    • mouth closed or near closed with corners of the mouth curving downward.
    • head tilted down, eyes darkened compared to face
    • bottom lip pressed up against the upper lip causing tightening of the chin

    • lips together, fewer lines in faces, no tension in the skin from expression distortions
    • face is much more squared up to the frame, much less tilt or angles in the faces.
    • eyebrows straight across, not raised or furrowed, no tension

Observations and Insights:__

The distribution of the classes is almost perfectly equal. There are 5% less 'surprise' images in the dataset than the others.

This is an insignificant difference, outcomes shouldn't be affected.

Think About It:

  • Are the classes equally distributed? If not, do you think the imbalance is too high? Will it be a problem as we progress?
    • The imbalance does not seem too high to cause an issue. The difference is small, 5%, and it only impacts 1 of the 4 classes.
  • Are there any Exploratory Data Analysis tasks that we can do here? Would they provide any meaningful insights?
    • There are no more meaningful EDA left to perform that will draw out significant insights.

Facial Emotion Detection - Initial Model Building¶

Creating our Data Loaders¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network.

You have two options for the color_mode. You can set it to color_mode = 'rgb' or color_mode = 'grayscale'. You will need to try out both and see for yourself which one gives better performance.

In [16]:
# grayscale data loader
bw_datagen_train  = ImageDataGenerator()
bw_datagen_val = ImageDataGenerator()
bw_datagen_test = ImageDataGenerator()

bw_train_set = bw_datagen_train.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'train/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "grayscale",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

bw_validation_set = bw_datagen_val.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'validation/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "grayscale",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

Think About It:

  • Are Convolutional Neural Networks the right approach? Should we have gone with Artificial Neural Networks instead?
    • A: Yes, Convolutional Neural Networks are the correct approach because they are particularly suited to analyze images. An Articial Neural Network could work but its unlikely to perform better than the CNN.
  • What are the advantages of CNNs over ANNs and are they applicable here?
    • A: The largest advantage of CNN over ANN for this task is the CNN's utilization of convolution and pooling layers. The convolutional and pooling layers analyze, interpret, and extract features by 'passing' a smaller matrix 'over' the image's large pixel matrix. The smaller matrix acts as a filter as it progresses through the entire image's matrix reducing the data down to important features which then make up the next layer's 'image' to then be analyzed again and reduced further.

Creating the Base Neural Network¶

In [18]:
model_01 = Sequential()

model_01.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), padding = "same", input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

model_01.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

model_01.add(Conv2D(filters = 32, kernel_size = (3, 3), padding = 'same'))

model_01.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

model_01.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

model_01.add(Flatten())

model_01.add(Dense(30))

model_01.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

model_01.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

opt = Adam(learning_rate = 0.0001)

Creating the second Convolutional Neural Network¶

  • Try out a slightly larger architecture. Added layers and adjusted values. Will run this one with the bw color_mode dataset, and then right after do a run on the rgb color set for comparison.

  • Changes: Activation function changed from designated LeakyReLU layers to a 'relu' function inside some of the Conv2D layers. Changed the learning rate value.

In [24]:
model_02 = Sequential()

model_02.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = "same", input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

model_02.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_02.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

model_02.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

model_02.add(Dropout(0.25))

model_02.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_02.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2)))

model_02.add(Flatten())

model_02.add(Dense(50))

model_02.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

model_02.add(Dense(25))

model_02.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))

model_02.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

opt = Adam(learning_rate = 0.0005)

[0.9269284009933472, 0.6640625]

Observations and Insights:__

  • The use of the color_mode reduced the performance of this neural net's structure.
  • The model remains overfit. Validation data barely reached 50% accuracy while training was around 87%.
  • Not deployable.

Think About It:¶

  • Did the models have a satisfactory performance? If not, then what are the possible reasons?
  • Which Color mode showed better overall performance? What are the possible reasons? Do you think having 'rgb' color mode is needed because the images are already black and white?

Facial Emotion Detection - Model Building with Transfer Learning Architectures¶

In this section, we will create several Transfer Learning architectures. For the pre-trained models, we will select three popular architectures namely, VGG16, ResNet v2, and Efficient Net. The difference between these architectures and the previous architectures is that these will require 3 input channels while the earlier ones worked on 'grayscale' images. Therefore, we need to create new DataLoaders.

Creating our Data Loaders for Transfer Learning Architectures¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders that we will use as inputs to our Neural Network. We will have to go with color_mode = 'rgb' as this is the required format for the transfer learning architectures.

In [ ]:
# set up the random seeds for reproducability
backend.clear_session()

np.random.seed(1)
import random
random.seed(1)
tf.random.set_seed(1)
In [5]:
# rgb data loader

vgg_datagen_train  = ImageDataGenerator()
vgg_datagen_val = ImageDataGenerator()
vgg_datagen_test = ImageDataGenerator()

vgg_train_set = vgg_datagen_train.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'train/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "rgb",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

vgg_validation_set = vgg_datagen_val.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'validation/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "rgb",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

vgg_test_set = vgg_datagen_test.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'test/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "rgb",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

4/4 [==============================] - 0s 15ms/step - loss: 0.8384 - accuracy: 0.6719
Out[14]:
[0.8384191989898682, 0.671875]

Think About It:

  • What do you infer from the general trend in the training performance?
    • The general trend of the training performance is fairly consistent. There are a few moments of stagnation before the learning continues. Accuracy continues to climb up toward 90%.
  • Is the training accuracy consistently improving?
    • Consistently, no. Very few distruptions prevent a perfectly consistent improvement in accuracy.
    • Epoch 1 training and validation accuracies were impressive. The perforance from the 1st epoch to the 2nd had a reduction in performance. Training slightly slowed and validation performed worse.
  • Is the validation accuracy also improving similarly?
    • No, the validation's accuracy struggles to find a good consistency in performance. The validation accuracy performed well and early.
    • Epoch 5 is where the validation accuracy falls off a cliff. Drops from 70% to 55%. Model's performance never returned to 70& accuracy before training run ended.

Observations and Insights:__

  • The pretraining of the vgg model made the model perform extremely well on the training set. Accuracy was up around 90%. Increasing accuracy and reducing overfitting is more difficult.
  • learning rate is a powerful tool to help with transfer learning. The more subtle the adjustments to the weights will help hone in further the already tuned model weights.
  • I dont think my model above had a subtle enough learning rate. Model used 0.0001. I suspect a rate of 0.00001 would outperform the model above.
  • VGG may not be an ideal transfer learning model to use in this particular application since the dataset I am using is grayscale. VGG was trained on color photos so the input data must also be color_mode = 'rgb'

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the VGG16 Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance

ResNet V2 Model¶

In [ ]:
from keras import layers

Model Building¶

  • Import Resnet v2 upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [ ]:
x_train_use = keras.applications.resnet_v2.preprocess_input(X_train)
x_test_use = keras.applications.resnet_v2.preprocess_input(X_test)
x_val_use = keras.applications.resnet_v2.preprocess_input(X_val)

base_model = keras.applications.ResNet50V2(
    include_top = False,
    weights="imagenet",
    input_tensor=None,
    input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 3),
    pooling = 'max',
    classes=4,
    classifier_activation="softmax")

base_model.trainable = False

inputs = keras.Input(shape=(IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 3))
x = base_model(inputs, training = False)
x = keras.layers.Dense(128, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
x = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
x = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = Flatten()(x)
x = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)
x = keras.layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)


outputs = keras.layers.Dense(4, activation = 'softmax')(x)
model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

Observations and Insights:__

  • This model I tried to apply the theory from the previous model's observations about a more subtle learning rate. The learning rate of this model is 0.00001. The subtle adjustments in the model's weights allowed the performance on the training and validation sets to be very similar accuracies.

  • The training and validation sets reached 62% accuracy. The two datasets performances were very consistent with one another.

  • If I increased the amount of layers I introduce to the model, and if I unfreeze a portion of the transfered nodes perhaps the performance of the model will significantly increase.

  • The model's consistent performance is significant to me. The model performed best on the training set with a 63% accuracy.

  • Good, but not deployable.

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the ResNet Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance.

EfficientNet Model¶

This model caused a lot of colab crashes. I added a lot of the import and data loading back into this section as a way to help make crashes more efficient to manage.

In [4]:
#training data
DATADIR = '/content/Facial_emotion_images/train'
CATEGORIES = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise']
ef_net_size = 224

#create training data
ef_training_data = []

def make_ef_training_data():
  for category in CATEGORIES:
    path = os.path.join(DATADIR, category)
    classifier_number = category

    for img in os.listdir(path):
      array01 = cv2.imread(os.path.join(path, img))
      array02 = cv2.resize(array01, (ef_net_size, ef_net_size))
      ef_training_data.append([array02, classifier_number])

make_ef_training_data()

Model Building¶

  • Import EfficientNet upto the layer of your choice and add Fully Connected layers on top of it.
In [10]:
def build_ef_model(num_classes):
  inputs = layers.Input(shape = (224, 224, 3), tensor = None)
  model_ef = EfficientNetB0(include_top = False, input_tensor = inputs, input_shape = (224, 224, 3), weights = 'imagenet', classes = 4)

  model_ef.trainable = False

  x = layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D(name = 'avg_pool')(model_ef.output)
  x = layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
  x = layers.Dense(254, activation = 'relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dense(254, activation = 'relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
  x = layers.Dense(254, activation = 'relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dense(254, activation = 'relu')(x)
  x = layers.Flatten()(x)
  x = layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
  x = layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)
  x = layers.Dense(64, activation = 'relu')(x)

  outputs = layers.Dense(num_classes, activation = 'softmax', name = 'pred')(x)

  ef_model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs, name = 'EfficientNet')
  optimizer = Adam(learning_rate = 0.0001)
  ef_model.compile(optimizer = optimizer, loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy'])

  return ef_model

Evaluating the EfficientnetNet Model¶

In [13]:
def plot_hist(hist):
    plt.plot(ef_net_model_01.history["accuracy"])
    plt.plot(ef_net_model_01.history["val_accuracy"])
    plt.title("model accuracy")
    plt.ylabel("accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("epoch")
    plt.legend(["train", "validation"], loc="upper left")
    plt.show()


plot_hist(ef_net_model_01)

Observations & Insights:__

  • This model performed very well for me. Final training accuracy of 84% and a validation accuracy of 71%.

  • Despite a learning rate of 0.0001 the model is not too overfit. Yes, it is overfit, but its not pushing extremes.

  • Test set accuracy is 79% accurate. 79% accuracy on the test set while having a performance of 84% on the training is a great ratio for me.

  • Less than 5% difference in accuracies at the performance level around 80% is a model that can be deployed.

  • More adjustments and work and the performance on the model would improve.

Unfreeze the model and fine-tune training further¶

  • The model performed very well with all of the transfer layers untrainable. This next section is where some of the transfer layers will be allowed to train in an attempt to fine tune the well-performing model.

In [13]:
# unfreeze the model for fine tuning

def unfreeze_model(model):
  for layer in model.layers[-40:]:
    if not isinstance(layer, layers.BatchNormalization):
      layer.trainable = True
  optimizer = Adam(learning_rate = 0.000001)
  model.compile(
      optimizer = optimizer, loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy']
  )

unfreeze_model(new_efnet_model)

Observations and Insights:__

  • This result is a surprise to me. I expected the model to have increased performance but this output is strange to me.

  • The training data slowly climbed from 80% to 83% while the validation data nearly instantly had an accuracy above 90%

  • I dont understand why this happened. Perhaps there was data leakage and I did not unfreeze and re-use the model correctly.

  • Performance on the test data is slightly worse than the model this was intended to improve. Experiement didn't work to improve accuracy but there is something interesting to discover about the validation performance.

Note: You can even go back and build your own architecture on top of the VGG16 Transfer layer and see if you can improve the performance.

Think About It:

  • What is your overall performance of these Transfer Learning Architectures? Can we draw a comparison of these models' performances. Are we satisfied with the accuracies that we have received?
  • Do you think our issue lies with 'rgb' color_mode?

Now that we have tried multiple pre-trained models, let's build a complex CNN architecture and see if we can get better performance.

Facial Emotion Detection - More Complex Neural Network Architecture¶

In this section, we will build a more complex Convolutional Neural Network Model that has close to as many parameters as we had in our Transfer Learning Models. However, we will have only 1 input channel for our input images.

Creating our Data Loaders¶

In this section, we are creating data loaders which we will use as inputs to the more Complicated Convolutional Neural Network. We will go ahead with color_mode = 'grayscale'.

In [23]:
bw_datagen_train  = ImageDataGenerator()
bw_datagen_val = ImageDataGenerator()
bw_datagen_test = ImageDataGenerator()

bw_train_set = bw_datagen_train.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'train/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "grayscale",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

bw_validation_set = bw_datagen_val.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'validation/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "grayscale",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

bw_test_set = bw_datagen_test.flow_from_directory(folder_path + 'test/',
                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),
                                              color_mode = "grayscale",
                                              batch_size = 32,
                                              class_mode = 'categorical',
                                              classes = ['happy', 'neutral', 'sad', 'surprise'],
                                              shuffle = True)

In [ ]:
model_fin_3 = Sequential()

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 500, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = "same", input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 500, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(Dropout(0.2))

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 500, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 500, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 500, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_3.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2), padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_3.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_3.add(Flatten())

model_fin_3.add(Dense(45))

model_fin_3.add(Dense(45))

model_fin_3.add(Dense(45))

model_fin_3.add(Dense(45))

model_fin_3.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

opt = Adam(learning_rate = 0.00001)
In [ ]:
model_fin_3.compile(optimizer = opt, loss = 'categorical_crossentropy', metrics = ['accuracy'])

                                              target_size = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE),

# exact same model as the last one execpt this one is using data augmentation in an attempt to boost performances.

aug_model_fin = Sequential([

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = "same", input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)),

  data_augmentation,

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), padding = 'same', activation = 'relu'),

  layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2), strides = 2, padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2), strides = 2, padding = 'same'),

  layers.BatchNormalization(),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2), strides = 2, padding = 'same'),

  layers.BatchNormalization(),

  layers.Dropout(0.15),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2), strides = 2, padding = 'same'),

  layers.BatchNormalization(),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2), padding = 'same'),

  layers.BatchNormalization(),

  layers.Dropout(0.25),

  layers.Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'),

  layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size = (2, 2), padding = 'same'),

  layers.BatchNormalization(),

  layers.Flatten(),

  layers.Dense(50),

  layers.Dense(50),

  layers.Dense(50),

  layers.Dense(25),

  layers.BatchNormalization(),

  layers.Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'),

])

Observations & Insights:__

  • I am not certain the data augmentation was applied effectively. The model's performance is significantly reduced.

  • Performance on the validation set is very unstable, perhaps the data augmentations produced such chaotic accuracy readings.

  • Experiment didnt not achieve its goal of improving but interesting insights about the model's performance on validation data after some augmentations were found.

Model Iteration B Building¶

  • Try building a layer with 5 Convolutional Blocks and see if performance increases.

  • Iteration B

In [ ]:
model_fin_2 = Sequential()

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 500, kernel_size = (4, 4), activation = 'relu', padding = "same", input_shape = (IMG_SIZE, IMG_SIZE, 1)))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 350, kernel_size = (4, 4), strides = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 300, kernel_size = (4, 4), strides = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (2, 2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_2.add(Dropout(0.15))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (2, 2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 256, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (2, 2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (2, 2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (2, 2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), strides = (2, 2), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 128, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_2.add(Conv2D(filters = 64, kernel_size = (3, 3), activation = 'relu', padding = 'same'))

model_fin_2.add(MaxPooling2D(padding = 'same', pool_size = (2, 2)))

model_fin_2.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_2.add(Flatten())

model_fin_2.add(Dense(100))

model_fin_2.add(Dense(100))

model_fin_2.add(Dense(75))

model_fin_2.add(Dense(75))

model_fin_2.add(BatchNormalization())

model_fin_2.add(Dense(4, activation = 'softmax'))

opt = Adam(learning_rate = 0.00001)

Evaluating the Model on Test Set¶

In [ ]:
model_fin.evaluate(bw_test_set)

4/4 [==============================] - 0s 38ms/step - loss: 0.7345 - accuracy: 0.7969
Out[ ]:
[0.7344921827316284, 0.796875]

Observations and Insights:__

  • This custom build model has the highest performance numbers in the notebook but is very overfit.

  • The results on the testing data is 80%, which is good. The model's overfit but with 80% accuracy it still performs well.

  • Deployment is possible, more work can be done to reduce the overfitting. The learning rate on this is not as subtle as it could be.

# import the libraries for plotting the confusion matrix

from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# plot the confusion matrix

prediction = chosen_model.predict(ef_X_test)
pred = np.argmax(prediction, axis = 1)
y_true = np.argmax(ef_y_test_encoded, axis = 1)

print(classification_report(y_true, pred))

cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, pred)
plt.figure(figsize = (8, 5))

plt.ylabel('Actual')
plt.xlabel('Predicted')
plt.show()

Observations and Insights:__

  • The chosen model performed decent on the test data, the F1 Accuracy score is 74%.

  • The emotions 'sad' and 'surprise' performed very well, these facial emotions are more exaggerated.

  • The emotions 'happy' and 'neutral' performed okay, these facial emotions are much more subtle and can easily have overlapping traits to other emotion classes.

Facial Emotion Detection - Conclusions and Insights:¶

Insights¶

Refined insights:¶

  • What are the most meaningful insights from the data relevant to the problem?

    • Yes, it is possible for a computer to identify the expressions on a face. The configuration of the model and the quality of the training data are vital to control how accurate a model can correctly emotions.

    • The need for correctly and accurately labeled data is important to have high quality data for training. Facial expressions are subtle and determining the differences is difficult, even for humans at times.

    • The facial expressions that can manifest in subtle ways, 'happy' & 'neutral', are much harder for this model to predict correctly.

    • The facial expressions with bigger, usually unique, and easily recognizable features, 'sad' & 'surprised', are much easier for this model to predict correctly.

Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance:¶

  • How do different techniques perform? Which one is performing relatively better? Is there scope to improve the performance further?

    • The different technique had varying performances. Not only were the techniques different but the hyperparameters used would also change. Hard to do raw comparisons.

    • Overall, the best performing models had the more complex architectures. My personal best was a large complex custom framework. Second best was a transfer learning model.

    • Lots of room to explore and improve through manipulations of hyperparameters, data augmentation, additional training epochs on well performing models.

    • Adjustments to image sizes is also likely to improve performance of the model but will require more computational resources.

Proposal for the final solution design:¶

  • What model do you propose to be adopted? Why is this the best solution to adopt?

  • I propose the Fine-Tuned EfficientNet Model to be adopted because it had the 2nd highest performance of all tested models, 74%. It had the lowest loss value of all tested models, 0.61.

  • The model with the highest accuracy also had a high loss value. The slight decrease in performance of the proposed model is a value-added tradeoff for the big decrease in the loss value.
